# *java.time* 

The `java.util` Date-Time API and their formatting API, `SimpleDateFormat` are outdated and error-prone. It is recommended to stop using them completely and switch to the [modern Date-Time API](https://www.oracle.com/technical-resources/articles/java/jf14-Date-Time.html)&lt;sup&gt;*&lt;/sup&gt;.

A `java.util.Date` object simply represents an instant on the timeline — a wrapper around the number of milliseconds since the UNIX epoch (January 1, 1970, 00:00:00 GMT). Since it does not hold any timezone information, it is the JVM&#39;s timezone that gets applied by default while parsing/formatting using `SimeplDateFormat`, which could be the root cause of the problem in your case. 

**Solution using `java.time`, the modern Date-Time API:** Change the type of `date` field to [`LocalDate`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/time/LocalDate.html) as follows:

    public static void exampleMethod(
            @ApiParam(value = &quot;date&quot;, required = true)
            @DateTimeFormat(iso = DateTimeFormat.ISO.DATE) LocalDate date) {...}

Learn more about the modern Date-Time API from **[Trail: Date Time](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/datetime/index.html)**.

### In case you want to use `java.util.Date`:

As per the [documentation](https://docs.spring.io/spring-framework/docs/current/javadoc-api/org/springframework/format/annotation/DateTimeFormat.html#pattern--):

&gt; Whenever the [`iso()`](https://docs.spring.io/spring-framework/docs/current/javadoc-api/org/springframework/format/annotation/DateTimeFormat.html#iso--) attribute is used when formatting Date values, UTC
&gt; will be used as the time zone.

So, all you need to do is to use `iso()` attribute i.e.

    public static void exampleMethod(
            @ApiParam(value = &quot;date&quot;, required = true)
            @DateTimeFormat(iso = DateTimeFormat.ISO.DATE) Date date) {...}

***
&lt;sup&gt;* If you are working for an Android project and your Android API level is still not compliant with Java-8, check [Java 8+ APIs available through desugaring](https://developer.android.com/studio/write/java8-support-table). Note that Android 8.0 Oreo already provides [support for `java.time`](https://developer.android.com/reference/java/time/package-summary).
&lt;/sup&gt;

